# Day 02 - Operators in Python

## Topics Learned

- Assignment Operators
- Comparison Operators
- Logical Operators
- String Methods Revision
- String Indexing
- String Slicing
- Negative Indexing
- Negative Slicing
- f-Strings

---

## Assignment Operators

Used to assign or update values of variables.

### Operators
- =
- +=
- -=
- *=
- /=
- %=
- //=
- **=

### Example

```python
a = 10
a += 5
print(a)   # 15
```

---

## Comparison Operators

Used to compare two values.

Returns either **True** or **False**.

### Operators

- ==
- !=
- >
- <
- >=
- <=

### Example

```python
a = 10
b = 20

print(a == b)
print(a < b)
```

---

## Logical Operators

Used to combine conditions.

### Types

- and
- or
- not

### Example

```python
print(10 > 5 and 20 > 10)
print(10 > 20 or 5 < 10)
print(not(10 > 20))
```

---

## String Methods (Revision)

- len()
- upper()
- lower()
- strip()
- replace()

### Example

```python
name = "Shreyas"

print(len(name))
print(name.upper())
print(name.lower())
```

---

## String Indexing

Indexing is used to access a single character of a string.

Example:

```python
name = "Python"

print(name[0])   # P
print(name[-1])  # n
```

---

## String Slicing

Slicing is used to extract a part of a string.

Example:

```python
name = "Python"

print(name[0:3])   # Pyt
print(name[:4])    # Pyth
print(name[2:])    # thon
```

---

## Negative Slicing

Negative indexing starts from the end of the string.

Example:

```python
name = "Python"

print(name[-1])      # n
print(name[-3:])     # hon
```

---

## f-Strings

Used to print variables inside a string.

Example

```python
name = "Shreyas"

print(f"My name is {name}")
```

